{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1598"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1598"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.04,0.18,0.27,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50037"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1598"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35297"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"857"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50037"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThis contrast study was performed in this previously well 47-year-old woman after she had a CT scan performed for an episode of epigastric pain (Image). The CT scan had suggested that there was an area of abnormality in the upper digestive tract and that more detailed information could be obtained from a barium meal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Duodenal ulcer","Duodenal diverticulum","Choledocho-duodenal fistula","Malrotation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a \u003Cstrong\u003Emalrotation\u003C/strong\u003E. The duodenojejunal junction is normally situated to the left of the spinal process. In this case the junction lies over the body of the vertebra (Image 1)). This is a congenital malformation and in this case is of no clinical significance. It is almost certainly an incidental finding. The contrast study was done after the CT to get a clearer picture of the anatomy of the small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHere is an example of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eduodenal ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E, where contrast is visible in the ulcer crater (Image 2, 6). The next contrast shows a \u003Cstrong\u003Eduodenal diverticulum \u003C/strong\u003Efilled with contrast and visible on the medial border of the second part on the duodenum (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA g\u003Cstrong\u003Eastrointestinal stromal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen as a filling defect in the distal stomach (Image 4).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fifth X-ray is part of a contrast study looking at a sliding hiatus hernia, with contrast refluxing into the oesophagus and coincidentally there is contrast in the biliary tree from a choledocho-duodenal fistula (Image 5).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most congenital anomalies of the small intestine will present with obstructive symptoms."],"references":["Morris G, Kennedy A, Cochran W. Small Bowel Congenital Anomalies: a Review and Update. Current Gastroenterological Rep 2016; 18:16-28"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35297"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1598"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20197"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20717"},{"type":"media","id":"20718"},{"type":"media","id":"20719"},{"type":"media","id":"20720"},{"type":